    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="concession">
Ideally errors would not occur, especially catastrophic errors.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="11" relname="span"> Error recovery is a multi-faceted usability attribute.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="8" relname="span"> It is one of several aspects of the safety usability goal described by Preece (pg. 14-15).</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> Error recovery attempts to prevent users from carrying out unwanted actions.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="4" relname="circumstance"> Additionally, error recovery implies that when errors do occur, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="9" relname="span">they are easily overcome by providing various means of recovery.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="8" relname="volitional-result"> Taken in this context it is easy to understand why Preece included error recovery as a component of the safety usability goal.</segment>
